& [EnumeratedToribrotMathEngine] is a verified finite arithmetic execution substrate using addressed computation nodes, explicit digit representations, local operation tables, pants-style composition graphs, and replayable proof traces
  + [conversation_uuid] is 42c4c9ad-e962-4f5f-85ab-ed21ff7e118f
  + [canonical_specification_uuid] is 339838de-a2a2-4041-b9b4-92f9b09bc01f
  + [source_snapshot_uuid] is c2581602-856a-4cc1-bda3-0e3975716233
  + [source_document] is platform/source_documents/2026-05-19_enumerated_toribrot_math_engine/Toribrot Math Engine.source-snapshot.txt
  + [solution_uuid] is 0dee9469-0d88-4d06-a877-c0d1d72cd4b1
  + [primary_role] is arithmetic_proof_substrate
  + [not_primary_role] is RH_solver, zeta_theorem_engine, or universal_math_oracle
  + [architecture_layer_set] is RepresentationLayer, LocalArithmeticLayer, ExecutionGraphLayer, OperationProtocolLayer, VerificationLayer, and CallerBoundaryLayer
  + [binary_status] is one supported representation mode, not the identity of the engine
  + [address_module] is EnumeratedToribrotModule
  + [pants_status] is execution and proof composition graph, not a guarantee of mathematical insight by itself
  + [toribrot_status] is conceptual lineage and possible geometric caller, not the required shape of arithmetic correctness
  + [rh_status] is downstream numerical experiment support only

  = must: separate representation, local arithmetic, execution graph, operation protocols, verification, and callers
  = must: define all arithmetic through finite, inspectable operations with explicit precision or exactness boundaries
  = must: treat binary as Base = 2 within a general base/block representation discipline
  = must: treat pants nodes as typed operations with declared inputs and one output
  = must: verify computation bottom-up from leaves to root before claiming a checked result
  = must: expose precision, rounding, normalization, and approximation policy before supporting real, complex, logarithmic, exponential, or zeta computations
  = must: keep RH-related use downstream from the engine and limited to auditable finite numerical experiments
  - never: claim RH relevance from the arithmetic substrate alone
  - never: allow higher-level modules to hide numerical approximations behind the verified-integer engine
  - never: confuse Toribrot geometric recursion with the arithmetic correctness proof

## 1. Representation Layer

& [RepresentationLayer] is the data identity layer for values handled by the engine
  + [value_subject] is integer, rational, fixed_precision_real, fixed_precision_complex, interval, or symbolic_reference
  + [representation_base] is an integer base greater than or equal to 2
  + [block_size] is the count of base digits grouped into one local chunk
  + [digit_sequence] is least-significant-first unless an operation protocol explicitly declares otherwise
  + [sign_model] is unsigned_magnitude, signed_magnitude, twos_complement, or rational_sign
  + [scale_model] is exact_integer_scale, rational_denominator, fixed_binary_point, fixed_decimal_point, or interval_radius
  + [precision_policy] is exact, fixed_precision, adaptive_precision, or interval_bounded
  + [rounding_policy] is none, truncate, round_to_nearest, directed_floor, directed_ceiling, or interval_outward
  + [normalization_policy] is canonical digit range, carry normalization, denominator reduction, and sign normalization

  = must: declare value_subject before operation selection
  = must: declare representation_base and block_size before digit allocation
  = must: declare precision_policy and rounding_policy before non-exact operations
  = must: preserve exactness status with the value
  = must: use Base = 2 only when binary is the chosen representation mode
  - never: call an approximate value verified without its error or interval contract

& [ValueRecord] is one represented mathematical value
  + [value_id] is stable identifier for the represented value
  + [semantic_type] is integer, rational, fixed_precision_real, fixed_precision_complex, interval, or symbolic_reference
  + [representation] is RepresentationLayer fields plus digit_sequence or component references
  + [exactness_state] is exact, approximate_with_error_bound, approximate_without_bound, or symbolic
  + [component_set] is real_part, imaginary_part, numerator, denominator, mantissa, exponent, lower_bound, or upper_bound when required

  = must: preserve component identity when complex, rational, or interval values are decomposed

## 2. Node And Address Layer

& [ComputationNode] is one addressed unit in a finite computation graph
  + [address] is ToribrotAddress from EnumeratedToribrotModule
  + [generation] is len(address) - 1
  + [parent] is optional address
  + [input_edge_set] is ordered references to child or predecessor nodes
  + [output_edge_set] is references to dependent nodes
  + [node_role] is OperandLeaf, DigitCell, CarryCell, PartialProduct, PartialSum, QuotientDigit, Remainder, ApproximationStep, VerificationStep, or FinalResult
  + [operation_ref] is optional OperationRecord
  + [value_ref] is optional ValueRecord
  + [local_state] is digit, block, carry_in, carry_out, table_result, error_bound, or interval
  + [verification_state] is unverified, verified, failed, skipped, or blocked
  + [proof_trace] is optional structured explanation for recomputing this node

  = must: allocate only the finite graph required by the active computation
  = must: keep address identity stable after allocation
  = must: follow EnumeratedToribrotModule for root address, generation, parent, and child rules
  = must: distinguish tree address from dependency graph edges when operations share intermediate results

& [ComputationGraph] is the finite graph instantiated for one problem
  + [graph_id] is stable computation identifier
  + [node_set] is finite set of ComputationNode
  + [edge_set] is data dependency edges between nodes
  + [root_node] is the output node for the requested operation
  + [graph_shape] is tree, DAG, or sequence
  + [allocation_policy] is lazy, eager, or planned

  = must: allow DAG structure when sharing intermediate results is meaningful
  = must: preserve pants-node semantics even when address storage is binary tree shaped
  - never: infer dependency only from binary address ancestry when explicit operation edges differ

## 3. Local Arithmetic Layer

& [LocalArithmeticLayer] is the finite set of atomic operations used by operation protocols
  + [AddBlock] maps block_a, block_b, carry_in to sum_block and carry_out
  + [SubBlock] maps block_a, block_b, borrow_in to difference_block and borrow_out
  + [MulBlock] maps block_a and block_b to product_block_pair or widened_product
  + [CompareBlock] maps block sequences to less_than, equal, or greater_than
  + [ShiftBlock] maps digit sequence and shift amount to shifted sequence
  + [NormalizeBlock] maps raw block sequence to canonical digit range and final carries

  = must: define each atomic operation by formula or exhaustive table
  = must: exhaustively test table-backed atomic operations for the selected base and block_size
  = must: preserve carry and borrow semantics as explicit local state
  - never: hide carry propagation inside an unrecorded helper

## 4. Operation Protocol Layer

& [OperationRecord] is the declared operation performed at one pants node or operation subtree
  + [op_type] is Add, Sub, Mul, Div, Compare, Shift, Normalize, Exp, Log, Sin, Cos, ZetaTerm, or Custom
  + [input_value_set] is ordered ValueRecord references
  + [output_value] is ValueRecord reference
  + [parameter_set] is representation_base, block_size, precision_policy, rounding_policy, decomposition_strategy, and verification_mode
  + [precondition_set] is input validity constraints
  + [postcondition_set] is output validity constraints
  + [implementation_protocol] is reference to an operation protocol

  = must: declare op_type and parameters before graph execution
  = must: define preconditions and postconditions for nontrivial operations

& [AddProtocol] is exact or fixed-precision addition by block cells and carry propagation
  + [strategy] is SequentialCarry, CarryLookahead, or BalancedManyAdd

  = must: align digit positions
  = must: compute each output block through AddBlock and explicit carry state
  = must: normalize final carry

& [MulProtocol] is exact or fixed-precision multiplication by partial products and checked summation
  + [strategy] is ClassicalPartialProducts, KaratsubaLike, ToomLike, or Custom

  = must: generate partial product nodes with explicit positional shifts
  = must: combine partial products through AddProtocol or declared summation protocol
  = must: preserve widening and carry normalization

& [DivProtocol] is quotient and remainder computation under declared exactness and precision policy
  + [strategy] is LongDivision, NewtonReciprocal, IntervalDivision, or Custom

  = must: reject zero divisor before allocation
  = must: define quotient digit selection and correction rules
  = must: preserve remainder invariant when exact division is requested
  = must: preserve error bounds when approximate division is requested

& [TranscendentalProtocol] is the boundary for exp, log, trigonometric, and special-function operations
  + [supported_method] is series, argument_reduction_plus_series, NewtonIteration, binary_splitting, interval_method, or external_oracle_with_proof
  + [error_contract] is required for every approximate result
  + [primitive_dependency] is AddProtocol, MulProtocol, DivProtocol, CompareBlock, and NormalizeBlock

  = must: define convergence domain and error bound before use
  = must: produce interval or certified error when used for analytic experiments
  - never: treat transcendental approximations as verified merely because their internal arithmetic is verified

## 5. Pants Execution Layer

& [PantsExecutionLayer] is the decomposition discipline for composing operations
  + [pants_node] is a typed operation node with two primary inputs and one output
  + [arity_adapter] is a deterministic decomposition that converts many-input or unary operations into binary composition steps
  + [composition_graph] is a tree or DAG of pants_node operations
  + [intermediate_value] is stored output of a pants_node

  = must: decompose many-input operations into explicit binary composition graph
  = must: allow unary operations only when represented as an operation node with one value input and parameter input or as a declared unary adapter
  = must: preserve intermediate_value references for audit and replay
  - never: use pants vocabulary as a substitute for operation contracts

## 6. Verification Layer

& [VerificationLayer] is the proof and replay system for a computation graph
  + [verification_mode] is off, atomic_only, full_graph, sampled, or interval_certified
  + [leaf_check] verifies operand digit encoding against input ValueRecord
  + [atomic_check] recomputes table or formula outputs for local operations
  + [composition_check] verifies parent operation result from child outputs
  + [invariant_check] verifies declared preconditions, postconditions, and remainder or error invariants
  + [root_certificate] is accepted only when required checks pass

  = must: verify leaves before internal nodes
  = must: verify operation outputs bottom-up
  = must: mark failed nodes with fault reason
  = must: preserve proof_trace for every checked operation when audit mode is enabled
  = must: distinguish exact verification from approximate error certification

## 7. Caller Boundary Layer

& [CallerBoundaryLayer] is the interface between the arithmetic engine and higher-level systems
  + [caller] is Toribrot, ZetaOscilloscope, Zetabrot, Base60PrimeSieve, or another module
  + [request] is OperationRecord or computation graph request
  + [response] is ValueRecord plus verification certificate or fault
  + [caller_responsibility] is declaring mathematical model, precision needs, and interpretation boundary
  + [engine_responsibility] is executing and verifying the finite arithmetic request

  = must: require callers to declare precision and interpretation boundary
  = must: return verification_state with every result
  = must: let callers own mathematical meaning beyond arithmetic correctness
  - never: let callers claim analytic truth from arithmetic verification alone

& [RHExperimentBoundary] is the safe use contract for RH-adjacent numerical experiments
  + [valid_use] is finite zeta sums, finite prime-power phasor terms, explicit formula experiments, interval checks, or visualization data generation
  + [invalid_claim] is proof of RH, disproof of RH, direct zero certification without an established analytic method, or theorem inference from visual pattern
  + [required_support] is error bounds, cutoff policy, sampling policy, and independent cross-check when claims exceed visualization

  = must: use ZetaOscilloscope or another analytic caller to define RH-adjacent quantities before arithmetic execution
  = must: attach cutoff, smoothing, and error contracts to zeta-related computations
  = must: preserve numerical result as evidence, not proof, unless connected to a valid theorem-level argument
  - never: call the engine an RH analyzer by itself

## 8. Architecture Repair

& [ArchitectureRepair] is the correction from the source sketch to this canonical definition
  + [source_strength] is strong intuition for explicit node addressing, chunked local arithmetic, pants composition, and verification traces
  + [source_fault] is fusing arithmetic substrate, Toribrot geometry, and RH analysis into one over-authoritative engine
  + [repair] is layered separation with caller-owned analytic meaning and engine-owned arithmetic execution
  + [preserved_intent] is reliable auditable computation for downstream math experiments

  = must: preserve explicit enumeration as the core improvement path
  = must: downscope universal calculator claims to supported operation contracts
  = must: require each advanced operation to declare approximation and verification rules
  = must: make RH work downstream and evidence-bounded

